Backwards Elimination model.

be.mod <- mlr.mod 
#summary(be.mod)
be.mod <- update(be.mod, .~. -FG_pct) #update the model and remove least significant predictor
#summary(be.mod)
be.mod <- update(be.mod, .~. -FT_pct)
#summary(be.mod)
be.mod <- update(be.mod, .~. -THR_PA)
#summary(be.mod)
be.mod <- update(be.mod, .~. -BLK)
#summary(be.mod)
be.mod <- update(be.mod, .~. -REB)

AIC model

library("leaps") # used for AIC

Predicting the win percentage on the test data (current nba season).

mlr.pred <- predict(mlr.mod, newdata = test.data)

pers.pred <- predict(pers.mod, newdata = test.data)

be.pred <- predict(be.mod, newdata = test.data)

aic.pred <- predict(aic.mod, newdata = test.data)

pca.pred <- predict(pca.mod, newdata = test.data)

Using a table to examine actual win percentage and predicted win percentage. The team with the highest predicted win percentage are the Utah Jazz and therefore are our predicted 2022 NBA champions.

pred.table <- as.data.frame(x = test.data$TEAM)
names(pred.table)[names(pred.table) == "test.data$TEAM"] <- "Teams"
pred.table$Real_Win_pct <- test.data$W_pct
pred.table$Pred_Win_pct <- pers.pred

ggplot(data = pred.table, mapping = aes(Pred_Win_pct, Real_Win_pct)) + geom_point(color = "dark blue") + 
  geom_smooth() + xlab("Predicted Win Percentage") + ylab("Actual Win Percentage")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
